# Home-Lab Developer Tools - Cursor Rules

## Formatting
- Never use em dashes. Use a regular dash (-) or double dash (--) or rewrite the sentence.
- Never use emojis in any file.
- Never hardcode SSH credentials, IP addresses, or private keys. Always use environment variables.

## Plugin conventions
- Skills live in `skills/<skill-name>/SKILL.md` (one per directory, kebab-case).
- Rules live in `rules/<rule-name>.mdc`.
- Every skill SKILL.md must have YAML frontmatter with `name` (matching directory) and `description`.
- Every rule .mdc must have YAML frontmatter with `description` and `alwaysApply`.
- Skill sections in order: Trigger, Required Inputs, Workflow, Key References, Example Interaction, MCP Usage, Common Pitfalls, See Also.

## MCP server conventions
- Tool names follow `homelab_camelCase` pattern (e.g. `homelab_piStatus`, `homelab_serviceHealth`).
- Each tool file exports a `register(server)` function.
- All Pi interaction goes through SSH via `execSSH()` from `utils/ssh-api.ts`.
- Always check SSH connectivity before executing commands.
- Handle connection failures gracefully with typed errors.

## Release checklist
Before finalizing any version bump, complete every item in order:
1. Implement all MCP tools, skills, and rules listed for the milestone in ROADMAP.md.
2. Add input validation tests for every new MCP tool in `input-validation.test.ts`.
3. Build the MCP server (`npm run build`) and confirm zero compiler errors.
4. Run all tests: `cd mcp-server && npm test` (Vitest) and `pytest tests/ -v --tb=short` (structure).
5. Bump version in ALL of these files (must be consistent):
   - `.cursor-plugin/plugin.json` (version + description tool count)
   - `mcp-server/package.json` (version + description)
   - `mcp-server/src/index.ts` (McpServer version string)
   - `README.md` (version badge, tool count in tagline, tools table)
   - `CLAUDE.md` (version, tool count, tool table)
   - `ROADMAP.md` (mark new version as current, previous as Released)
6. Add a new section to `CHANGELOG.md` with all Added/Changed/Fixed items.
7. Update GitHub repo About description with new counts: `gh repo edit --description "...N skills, N rules, and N MCP tools..."`.
8. Update `docs/index.html` (GitHub Pages site):
   - Meta description and og:description tool counts
   - Hero version pill
   - Stats counter data-target for MCP Tools
   - Tools table (add new tool rows)
9. Regenerate `package-lock.json` by running `npm install` in `mcp-server/` after version bump.
10. Re-run all tests after doc changes (some tests validate docs consistency).
11. Commit everything (including `package-lock.json`) and push to `main`. The `auto-tag.yml` workflow creates the tag and release automatically.
12. Verify the release appears on GitHub and npm publish succeeds.

## Publishing flow
- Pushing a version bump in `mcp-server/package.json` to `main` triggers `auto-tag.yml`.
- `auto-tag.yml` detects the version change, creates a git tag (`vX.Y.Z`), creates a GitHub Release, then builds, tests, and publishes to npm -- all in one workflow.
- `publish.yml` exists as a manual fallback only (workflow_dispatch or manual GitHub Release).
- Release Drafter auto-drafts release notes from merged PRs (labels control categories).
- Never publish to npm manually -- always go through the automated workflow.
- Never create tags or releases manually -- `auto-tag.yml` handles this automatically on version bumps.

## Home lab conventions
- Target platform is Raspberry Pi 5 running Raspberry Pi OS Lite 64-bit (arm64).
- Docker Compose stacks live in `/opt/homelab/docker/` on the Pi.
- Compose files are split by function: base, monitoring, network, apps, security, storage, tools.
- Native services (Cockpit, Samba, node_exporter) are managed via systemd, not Docker.
